</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A7FE6554FFCAFFF4FF08FEDA6E945C32" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="EF5B36DFFFCAFFF4FF08FEDA6E945C32" blockId="8.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FF08FEDA6B395F36" bold="true" box="[199,308,259,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">Remarks</emphasis>
. In the key by 
<bibRefCitation id="8B754B2EFFCAFFF4FE2FFEDA68B65F36" author="zur Strassen, R." box="[480,699,259,285]" journalOrPublisher="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" pagination="1 - 277" part="74" refId="ref9421" refString="zur Strassen, R. (2003) Die terebranten Thysanopteren Europe. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, 74, 1 - 277." title="Die terebranten Thysanopteren Europe" type="journal article" year="2003">zur Strassen (2003)</bibRefCitation>
this species runs to 
<taxonomicName id="28E44D5CFFCAFFF4FC6EFEDA6E2C5F36" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1990" box="[929,1057,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramadei">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FC6EFEDA6E2C5F36" box="[929,1057,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">O. ramadei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is described from 
<collectingCountry id="97F3764FFFCAFFF4FA8EFEDA6F7B5F36" box="[1345,1398,259,285]" name="Italy" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">Italy</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="28E44D5CFFCAFFF4FA4EFEDA6AD25F6A" authority="Alavi &amp; Minaei, 2022" authorityName="Alavi &amp; Minaei" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitkini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FA4EFEDA6AD25F6A" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">O. pitkini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FF28FEFE6B2A5F6A" bold="true" box="[231,295,295,321]" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="C6A357B6FFCAFFF4FF28FEFE6B2A5F6A" box="[231,295,295,321]" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="28E44D5CFFCAFFF4FE90FEFE6BD25F6A" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1990" box="[351,479,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramadei">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FE90FEFE6BD25F6A" box="[351,479,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">O. ramadei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique among the known species of 
<taxonomicName id="28E44D5CFFCAFFF4FC60FEFE6E495F6A" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[943,1092,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FC60FEFE6E495F6A" box="[943,1092,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">Odontothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having antennal segment II with a tooth distally on the inner margin. These species are also similar in lacking teeth on the fore tarsi, having one small tooth at the fore tibia apex, and fore wing banded particularly in males. The females of these two species are not distinguishable, but the male of the new species is different from the male of 
<taxonomicName id="28E44D5CFFCAFFF4FBDBFE4A6E9F5F86" authorityName="Bournier" authorityYear="1990" box="[1044,1170,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramadei">
<emphasis id="DD90EACDFFCAFFF4FBDBFE4A6E9F5F86" box="[1044,1170,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">O. ramadei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in lacking canaliculi, in lacking a sub-apically directed strong tooth on the parameres (see 
<bibRefCitation id="8B754B2EFFCAFFF4FC4EFE6E6E2A5FFA" author="Bournier" box="[897,1063,439,465]" firstAuthor="Bournier" pageId="8" pageNumber="387" pagination="199 - 206" refId="ref8170" refString="Bournier, A. (1990) Contributions la connaissance du genre Odontothrips Amyot et Serville (Thys. Thripidae). Bulletin de la Societ entomologiqe de France, 95, 199 - 206. https: // doi. org / 10.3406 / bsef. 1990.17655" type="journal article" year="1990">Bournier 1990</bibRefCitation>
, p. 201, 
<figureCitation id="77DF2A5AFFCAFFF4FB48FE6E6ED55FF9" box="[1159,1240,439,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,846,1153]" captionTargetId="figure-365@2.[151,1435,846,1153]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Odontothrips species. (1–3) Fore tarsus and apex of fore tibia, female: (1) O. meliloti, (2) O. moritzi, (3) O. confusus. (4–5) Abdominal tergites XI–X and genitalia, male: (4) O. meliloti, (5) O. confusus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450821/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
), and in having a series of dorsal fine ridges on the parameres medially (
<figureCitation id="77DF2A5AFFCAFFF4FD39FE0269445FDE" box="[758,841,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–33" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1910,1934]" captionTargetBox="[173,1414,183,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[173,1414,181,1886]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 18–33. Odontothrips pitkini sp. n. Female 18–29: (18) body, (19) antennal segments I–VIII, (20) antennal segments VI–VIII, (21–22) antennal segments I–III, (23–25) fore tarsus and apex of fore tibia (25 lateral views), (26) head &amp; pronotum, (27) meso- &amp; metanotum, (28) abdominal tergites VIII–X, (29) fore wing. Male 30–33: (30) body, (31) fore wing, (32) abdominal sternites IV– VII, (33) abdominal tergites XI–X and genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450827/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="387">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). The male of 
